    bridge_15: null,
    penny_moment: `Penny held a coin up to the light this morning. It caught the sun in a small way. She kept turning it over. It was just a small disc of metal. And yet — somehow — everyone agrees it means something. She is still thinking about that.`,
    penny_mode: `co-discoverer`,
    app_text_59: `A coin is just a small piece of metal. A note is just paper. But everyone agrees to treat them as something important — and that agreement is what makes them real. Isn't that strange? What would you do with a coin if nobody agreed it meant anything?`,
    app_text_1014: `A ₹100 note is just paper. It is worth ₹100 only because every shopkeeper, parent, and stranger agrees it is. That agreement — shared by everyone simultaneously — is what money actually is. It is not a thing. It is a belief.`,
    app_text_15: `You have probably never stopped to ask why a ₹500 note is worth ₹500. The answer is stranger than it looks: it is worth that because everyone — simultaneously, without being asked — agrees it is. That collective agreement can hold for centuries. It can also break. What makes it hold?`,
    dinner_prompt: `If you had to explain to a five-year-old why a piece of paper is worth something, what would you say?`,
    portfolio_status: `NOT APPLICABLE`,
