    topic: `Where does money come from?`,
    is_consolidation: false,
    bridge_59: `Penny is still thinking about that coin from last week. The one that could become almost anything. She keeps wondering: where did it come from in the first place?`,
    bridge_1014: `Last week's idea — that money is just an agreement — keeps pulling at something. If that's true, then where does the agreement start? Who makes it real?`,
    bridge_15: `If money is only worth something because everyone agrees it is, that raises a sharper question: where does the value actually come from?`,
    penny_moment: `Penny watched the chai-wallah this morning. He made fifty cups. People came, gave him coins, took the chai. He made more chai. The coins kept moving. Penny noticed the same thing at the vegetable stall, the auto-rickshaw, the school tuck shop. Useful things keep coins moving. She thought: does anything move coins that isn't useful?`,
    penny_mode: `co-discoverer`,
    app_text_59: `Every coin or note you have came from somewhere — from someone doing something useful enough that another person was willing to pay. The chai-wallah makes chai. The driver drives. What useful thing does your family do that brings coins home?`,
    app_text_1014: `Money flows toward things that are useful to other people. Every rupee in your family's life arrived because someone did something worth paying for — a skill, a service, a product. That is active income. There is another type, but we will get to that.`,
    app_text_15: `Most income requires continuous effort — stop working, stop earning. A few income sources do not work that way. Your family almost certainly relies primarily on the first type. What would change if some income arrived without anyone doing anything new?`,
    dinner_prompt: `What is one thing someone in our family does that people find useful enough to pay for — and how did they figure out that was the right thing to do?`,
