    cycle: 1,
    arc: `Arc 1`,
    topic: `Needs vs wants`,
    is_consolidation: false,
    bridge_59: `Penny thought about all the useful things people do to bring coins home. But then she noticed something: once the coins are there, you have to decide. And deciding is harder than it sounds.`,
    bridge_1014: `Money flows to useful things. But once it arrives, it faces a different problem — there is never quite enough of it for everything at once.`,
    bridge_15: `Every rupee earned came from something valuable. Which makes what you do with it next the more interesting question.`,
    penny_moment: `Penny watched two squirrels at the base of the oak tree. One had found a large pile of seeds. The other had found a smaller pile. The one with less chose carefully — first the heaviest seeds, then the ones that would last longest. The one with more grabbed randomly and dropped half. At the end of the day, both had enough. But only one had been thoughtful. Penny noticed that having less sometimes makes you sharper.`,
    penny_mode: `narrator`,
    app_text_59: `Some things matter more than others — especially when you cannot have both. Food is different from a new toy. A warm coat is different from extra sweets. If you only had coins for one today, which would you pick — and why?`,
    app_text_1014: `Every rupee spent on one thing closes a door on everything else that rupee could have become. You probably make this trade-off already — choosing between things with limited money. The important question is not what you chose. It is how you decided.`,
    app_text_15: `Every purchase has a hidden second price: the best thing you gave up to have it. That cost is real even when it is invisible. Most buying decisions happen without ever naming what the second price was. What is the second price of the last significant thing your family bought?`,
    dinner_prompt: `If our family had to cut one regular expense that we would barely miss, what would it be — and what does that tell us?`,
    portfolio_status: `NOT APPLICABLE`,
    portfolio_reference: `Opportunity cost concept best anchored in everyday spending experience, not portfolio.`,
