    arc: `Arc 1`,
    topic: `Spending choices`,
    is_consolidation: false,
    bridge_59: `Penny noticed that some things matter more than others when you cannot have both. That feeling of choosing — it stays with you a little, doesn't it?`,
    bridge_1014: `Every purchase closes a door on something else. That is easy to understand but harder to feel in the moment — when you are actually about to spend.`,
    bridge_15: `The hidden second price of a purchase is easy to see in theory. What is harder is making decisions before the moment arrives, not during it.`,
    penny_moment: `Penny told the young ones about something she had seen. A squirrel who decided — before leaving the tree — that she would only carry back four acorns today. No more, whatever she found. When she spotted a fifth large acorn later, she left it. She came home with exactly four, as planned. Penny thought: the decision before the walk was different from the decision during the walk. The calm moment was smarter.`,
    penny_mode: `narrator`,
    app_text_59: `Here is a trick the best decision-makers use: they decide before the moment arrives. Before going to the shop, they decide what they will buy. When feelings are calm, decisions are better. Do you have anything you want to buy soon? Could you decide now, before you are standing right in front of it?`,
    app_text_1014: `Decisions made in calm moments are almost always better than decisions made when you are right in front of the thing you want. The feeling of wanting something in the moment is real — but it is not reliable information. What is one spending rule your family could set before the situation arrives?`,
    app_text_15: `Impulsive spending is not a character flaw. It is a predictable response to in-the-moment exposure. The counter-move is making the decision before exposure — not relying on willpower in the moment. What decision-before-the-moment could your family make for the category where you overspend most?`,
    dinner_prompt: `Think of a time someone in our family made a spending decision they later regretted — what was happening in the moment, and what would the calm version of that decision have looked like?`,
