    cycle: 1,
    arc: `Arc 1`,
    topic: `Saving basics`,
    is_consolidation: false,
    bridge_59: `Penny sat with that feeling — when coins are gone, they are really gone. And then she wondered: what if some of them didn't have to be?`,
    bridge_1014: `Once you know that spending has a real, permanent consequence, something shifts. You start noticing the gap between what comes in and what stays.`,
    bridge_15: `The families that end up ahead figured out one thing before most: it is not what you earn that matters. It is what you keep.`,
    penny_moment: `Penny had an experiment this week. She gathered twelve acorns — her whole week's find. She split them carefully: some for now, some kept aside. At the end of the week, the ones set aside were still there. They had not disappeared. She kept turning this over: the ones she used were gone. The ones she kept were still real. The difference was just the decision.`,
    penny_mode: `co-discoverer`,
    app_text_59: `When you use up coins, they are gone — really gone. But the ones you keep are still there. Still yours. Still real. Every coin kept is a door that stays open. What would it feel like to keep even a small amount from every pile that comes your way?`,
    app_text_1014: `It is not what you earn that matters most. It is what you keep. Even a small kept amount, done consistently, creates something an income without saving never does: a growing pile that belongs to no one but you.`,
    app_text_15: `Savings rate is more predictive of long-term wealth than income level. A person earning ₹50,000 a month who keeps 30% will accumulate more over a lifetime than one earning ₹1,50,000 who keeps 5%. Which number does your family optimise for?`,
    dinner_prompt: `When [income or pocket money arrives], what is the first thing our family does with it?`,
