    arc: `Arc 1`,
    topic: `Goal setting`,
    is_consolidation: false,
    bridge_59: `Penny noticed that keeping some makes the pile grow. But a pile growing towards nothing feels different from a pile growing towards something. What is yours growing towards?`,
    bridge_1014: `A savings rate is more powerful than income. But powerful for what? That is the question that turns a habit into something real.`,
    bridge_15: `Keeping the biggest slice is the move. But a number without a direction is just discipline for its own sake. Goals turn the number into a plan.`,
    penny_moment: `Penny checked the goal jar this morning — the one your family set up. It is filling. Not full yet, but fuller than it was. She thought about how different a growing pile feels when it has a name on it. This one has a name. That changes everything about it.`,
    penny_mode: `companion`,
    app_text_59: `Your family has a goal. It has a name. It has a number. That makes it different from just saving — now the pile is working towards something real. Look at your goal in the app. How far has it come? How far does it have to go?`,
    app_text_1014: `Any goal, reversed, becomes a monthly number. Take the target. Subtract what is already saved. Divide by the months available. That number — often smaller than expected — is what consistent action costs. Your family's goal is in the app. What does the monthly number look like?`,
    app_text_15: `A goal without a reverse calculation is a wish. A goal with a specific monthly number, a timeline, and a starting amount is a plan. The difference in probability of achievement between the two is large. Look at your family's goal. What does the reverse calculation say?`,
    dinner_prompt: `If we decided on one family financial goal this week, what would it be — and what would the first small step look like?`,
